ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: The first thing I notice when I put on makeup these days is that drawing eyeliner has gotten a lot easier. Just draw along the line and it sets the shape perfectly, so I don't have to erase and retouch like I used to, which is so amazing. LOL. Even with a bare face, my eyes are so defined, and I often hear people around me tell me my face looks more defined. Whenever I hear, "Your eyes look prettier," I feel like I made a good choice. LOL. But it wasn't like this from the beginning. It's been about four months since I had the surgery. Now that the swelling has all gone down and my eyes have completely settled, when I look in the mirror these days, it feels like my eyes were always like this. It's almost as if I can't even remember what my eyes used to look like... LOL. This time, I not only had revision double eyelid surgery, but I also had upper eyelid surgery and lower eyelid surgery (popcorn surgery) all at once. People say that my eyes look longer both from the sides and down. In particular, the stuffy feeling at the corners of my eyes and under my eyes has been reduced, so many people tell me that my face looks softer, and that's what I like the most. I originally had my first double eyelid surgery without incisions, but as time went on, the lines gradually loosened, and eventually double eyelids developed. It was incredibly stressful. My eyes looked smaller, so I'd try filters every time I took a photo, and just looking at my eyes would bother me. That's how I went through those times. So, I was incredibly worried about getting my second surgery, but this time I went with natural adhesion. Afterward, the lines felt much more stable, and it didn't look like anything overdone. It felt like my eyes were just my own, which was what I was most satisfied with. I had my surgery done by a female director at Ttuk Plastic Surgery. From the very beginning, she meticulously asked me about my concerns and desired direction. Even when we discussed the design, I had a clear idea of the right approach. She guided me in the direction of the surgery, just as I'd suggested, and I still remember her. I'm sure many people have been troubled by double eyelid ruptures, double eyelids, or ambiguous lines. I, too, had to worry for a long time before my second surgery. Anyway, if you're looking for a review like this, I think you can just look at my current situation as a reference.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: First, let's talk about the hospital. I had surgery at Thank You Plastic Surgery by Director Kim Gyu-beom. From the consultation, he was very thorough and detailed, and he spoke honestly, not just giving me compliments. That's when I started trusting him. So, I naturally ended up entrusting him with the entire procedure. I had three procedures done at once: natural adhesion double eyelid surgery, upper eyelid surgery, and lower eyelid fat repositioning. I originally had an in-out line, but I always wanted a style where the line was clearly visible even when my eyes were open, so I emphasized that point a lot during the consultation. After the surgery, when the line settled, I looked in the mirror and it was exactly what I'd imagined. It wasn't overdone, but it was so visible when I opened my eyes that I loved it. Especially because I had natural adhesion double eyelid surgery and upper eyelid surgery, my eyes look so much more defined than before. Every time I wash my face and look in the mirror, I find myself taking a second look. I just thought I'd do the lower eyelid fat repositioning while I was lying down, but I ended up liking it more than I thought. The area under my eyes feels much brighter than before, so my entire face looks a bit younger. People around me often ask me why I look so young these days and say my face looks much smoother, and I can't help but laugh every time I hear that. Haha. The overall results of the surgery were almost exactly what I expected, so I'm realizing that trusting them in the beginning was a good choice.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: These days, every time I look in the mirror, I think, "Why do my eyes look so lifeless?" It's this thought that comes to mind. I feel like I look more tired than before, and it's been secretly stressing me out. When I first got double eyelid surgery, I was so happy. I thought, "Wow, I finally have lines!" and took a lot of selfies for no reason. But after a few months, the lines on both sides gradually faded and eventually just disappeared altogether. On both sides, on both sides... there was no such thing as lines. Since both sides were fading, even double eyelids couldn't cover them. Because my eyes are shaped awkwardly, eyeliner feels smudged, and makeup doesn't suit me, and the overall look feels dull. So I started to wonder, "Should I get this done again?" But since it was my second surgery, I didn't want to just rush into it, so I just mulled it over for a long time. Then one night, while searching for reviews of eye revision surgeries, I came across a particularly large number of reviews from the female director of Thank You Plastic Surgery. There are quite a few posts about people getting re-surgery due to natural adhesion, and many stories about their sagging eyelids being realigned and naturally positioned, so I thought, "Can I trust this?" Seeing people say their eye lines have become more defined again makes me a little bit more inclined... I haven't made a decision on getting the surgery right away and am still looking into it, but right now, I feel a little depressed every time I look in the mirror, so I really want to get my eye lines straight again. I completely agree with the saying that the aftermath of eye surgery is much more important than the first. I think there are many people like me who are worried because both eyes have come loose, so I'm reading other people's reviews and slowly considering re-surgery. For those in a similar situation, I hope you'll read up on reviews and think about it slowly together... ?

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: Because of the fat on my arms, I was really stressed out about wearing clothes. It was to the point where I couldn't even wear tight-fitting t-shirts or shirts... Even when I dieted, it felt like I was losing weight, but my arms stayed all the way. When I looked at them from the outside, they looked like they were just floating? LOL Especially in the winter, when I wore thick clothes, they looked even puffier, so I was even more concerned. So I looked into liposuction at one point, but I thought it was a bit hesitant to get surgery while working, so I just put it off. Then I heard about liposuction injections, so I searched a lot and found 247 Plastic Surgery near Sinnonhyeon Station, so I went there. The date was Friday, December 8, 2017, and I got 5 injections on each arm, 10 in total. The ladies who consulted with me were very kind and explained everything well, and they talked to me as if I was talking to them, so I didn't feel pressured. The needle wasn't as thick as I thought, and when they injected it, I was like, "Ouch!!" It didn't hurt that much. The procedure was over quickly, so I thought it would be okay for people who go to work to come at the right time. I took a picture of my arm right after the procedure, and this morning, exactly one week later, I took another picture of my arm to compare them. I could see changes in the line and size. The next day, there was a slight bruise the size of a fingernail, but it quickly faded in a day or two, so I didn't care. There was almost no pain, so it didn't interfere with my daily life. I was a little nervous because it was my first time receiving the procedure, but the director did his best to make it less painful when giving the injection and was very kind overall, so I was grateful.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I'm leaving a quick review of the 247 Clinic's Hanbyeon injection. First of all, I'd gotten abdominal liposuction here before, so I was familiar with the hospital and went back. The results weren't bad, so I was hesitant this time and decided to go here again. I'd been researching various contouring injections, and the Hanbyeon injection here was a bit pricier than other places. However, after hearing about it during the consultation, I thought it was effective, so I decided to try just one injection first. I got it on November 24th. What was surprising was... the injection didn't hurt, so I was a little taken aback. The nurse pinched my skin really hard, and I thought she was intentionally drawing attention to that area to make it less painful. But it really didn't hurt at all, so I just had a little bruise. Haha. I got it in two places: my double chin and my cheeks, and the photos were taken from almost the same angle. I decided to exchange the difference for a four-injection voucher after the first injection(?). I'm planning to go get it done again tomorrow, so I'll write another review after that's done.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I've been contemplating getting liposuction done on my butt for a long time, but I finally did it. LOL. My butt wasn't exactly perfect, but I couldn't stop wanting to get it done. I looked through tons of reviews on apps and on hospital websites. One place that looked the most like my butt after-shave look caught my eye, so I went for a consultation, paid on the spot, and made a reservation. My original plan was to also get liposuction on my thighs. So I asked the doctor to do that too, but he said my thighs aren't particularly thick. He said I need some thigh support to prevent sagging if I get liposuction on my butt. He also said that if I get both, my legs will swell a lot and the recovery period will be long, so I decided to just get liposuction on my abdomen. He also said they do a better job of reducing the waistline than other clinics, so I trusted that. The photos are too close to show, but my waist has gotten a lot thinner. I can definitely feel it, lol. I'm taking painkillers and anti-inflammatory medication, but it still hurts... They told me to lie face down, so I am, but it's harder than I thought. I can't just stay like that forever, so I'm alternating between my left and right sides. I have a bit of a hip, so they said they wouldn't push it in too much, so I'm a little less worried about it pressing down? They said it did, though, and the area next to my buttocks where there wasn't any fat has definitely filled in, so it feels full. Before the surgery, I watched a video of a hospital where a medical accident had recently occurred and resolved to never wear a mask. So I had the surgery under general anesthesia, but I didn't wear a mask. The hospital didn't even tell me to wear a mask. They told me not to take off the compression garment, so I skipped the shower. They told me to come back tomorrow, so I have to go again. This is my review from the day of the surgery. I'll take another picture and post it once I take the garment off.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: This picture was taken about two weeks after liposuction on my abdomen, love handles, and back, along with a hip lift, buttock fat grafting, and buttock wrinkle correction. I don't have a completely flat pelvis, and my buttocks weren't completely devoid of volume, but I had previously had thigh liposuction and a bit of hip reduction. After that, my buttocks looked slightly saggy from behind or at a 45-degree angle. The under-butt wrinkles from the liposuction and my wide pelvis made my hip dip even more noticeable, which really bothered me... So this time, I thought simply adding fat wouldn't do, so I combined it with a hip lift. I remember using a thread called Epiticon for the lift, and perhaps because I combined it with the lift, it felt like it supported the weight of my buttocks from below. I was worried that the thread lift would cause sagging again, but they also grafted fat above the threads, so even if the threads melt, the remaining fat would provide some support. I was told that the volume and sagging would remain to some extent over time. On the day of the surgery, the swelling was so bad that I almost felt like Kim Kardashian, lol. My priority was to lift up my sagging butt, fill in my hip dip, and correct my buttock wrinkles rather than create a ton of volume. As the swelling went down, I felt like I was getting closer to the look I wanted. When choosing a hospital, I wanted to avoid designs that were too obvious or styles that only placed a buttock bump on the top of the hip. I wanted the line that falls from the waist to the hip to flow naturally, and the director here designed the line exactly like that, so I decided to go here. Also, other places refused to touch up my buttock wrinkles, saying they were difficult to address, but here, they said they could improve them to some extent, so I trusted them with that as well. Now, the filled in hip dip is the first thing I notice, and thanks to it, my overall line looks much smoother. I really like the curve that runs from my waist to my pelvis, and the sagging hips have also been alleviated a lot compared to before, and the wrinkles under my buttocks are also getting better, so I especially like that part. The bruising from the liposuction area went down faster than I thought, so now only a little bit remains on my abdomen. There's still a little swelling. It feels a little lumpy to the touch, but it's not that bad. I'm getting high-frequency treatment at the hospital and observing it. They said it will smooth out more in a month or so, so I'm waiting. I think it would be okay if the overall volume was just slightly reduced, so I think I'd like it even more if the swelling went down a little more. I just hope the fat that filled my hip dip holds up well and doesn't sag. If I'm not satisfied with the implant placement or lifting, I'm considering adding more thread or a second fat graft, but for now, I'm pretty satisfied with the way it is. I'll write another review later when the swelling goes down and the fat has settled. I finished off with a before-after comparison shot. Haha. The wrinkles on the right side of my buttocks are still taped, so please take that into consideration when looking at them. Haha.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I was going to write again after the 4th week, but around the 3rd week, the feeling changed a bit, so I'm just going to write about it now, lol. I got a hip-up lift, hip filler, and liposuction on my back and sides all at once, so the bruising and swelling were really bad in the beginning. I'm the type of person who bruises don't go away easily, so there's still a little bit left on my back. Last week, when I went to check on the progress, the director said it was hard to see the lines yet and that the real shape would come out only after the bruising and swelling completely went down. Maybe that's why she suddenly showed me a picture of my butt that she took in the operating room right after the surgery, lol. The line I saw then was exactly the hip line I had imagined, so I was amazed... "Ah, so this is how it turned out..." Now, the residual swelling is almost gone compared to the 2nd week, and she said it would take about a month for the swelling to completely go down, so I'm just waiting. Personally, I think I'll get closer to the look I'm aiming for if the swelling on my left hip dip goes down a little more. My volume was significantly reduced compared to right after the surgery, which was a bit disappointing... but I had another retouch in the second week, so my hip line looks even prettier now. Funny enough, I had more fat than I expected, and they felt bad throwing it away, so they even gave me a facial fat graft as a freebie. I didn't know they had something like that, so I was even more surprised. People looking into plastic surgery hate the factory-style hospital atmosphere the most. I hate that too, which is why I chose this place. Everyone, from the director and information staff to the operating room staff and even the director, was incredibly kind. It didn't feel like a hospital that just gave up after the surgery, and they were meticulous about aftercare. As I mentioned in the photos, they even did things like radiofrequency and highlighting, which they don't usually do. I was very satisfied with the aftercare. I think I made a good choice, and I'll come back again once the swelling goes down a bit.

My lower body is generally thin, so it was even more noticeable, so I was about to give up, but then I had hip fat grafting and Epitique filler done by Dr. Jeong Yeong-chun of Hush. I received 200cc of filler, and he extracted fat from the front, sides, and back of my abdomen and transplanted it into my buttocks. I have a short waist, so he also worked on the lower back, giving me a more defined figure. I was amazed at how different my body line felt because he focused on removing that area. It's been exactly a month now, and since my pelvis has filled in, my hips have also come back to life. Every time I look in the mirror, I take a second look. Before, I didn't have any buttocks, so I couldn't tell even when I exercised my hips. But now, I like the silhouette of my clothes, so it's okay. The pain wasn't that bad, but I slept carefully and paid close attention to my posture for about a month. My sleeping position was a bit uncomfortable, but it was bearable. Now, a month has passed and I'm planning to start working out again. People like me who lack lower body volume will probably be really interested in this.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: The first thing I did after getting shoulder filler was... I went shopping for clothes. LOL. The day after the procedure, I went to Zara and tried on a bunch of different clothes. I used to think, "Why did the same clothes look so sloppy?" They now fit a little better. That's when I thought, "Wow, I did a great job!" Since then, I've felt like I'll be buying more clothes for a while, so my wallet is on the edge. LOL. I'm on the tall side, but my shoulders are narrow, so my upper body proportions are a bit off. I'm someone who always edits my shoulder line in photos... I used to habitually just stretch my shoulders for Instagram posts, thinking, "I can just keep doing that." I didn't even know shoulder fillers existed. But one day, I was reading reviews of shoulder fillers and was shocked. The exact same line I always used to adjust with the app was back there. That must have been something I was most concerned about, because people around me told me, "You should really get a consultation." After much deliberation, I decided to give it a try. I went back to the same clinic where I'd previously gotten a mini-contouring lift. First, during my consultation with the director, he checked everything from my shoulder to my collarbone. He examined me in detail and explained everything thoroughly, which put me at ease. Then, Director Jeong Yeong-chun explained everything in detail, including my shoulder line, the direction of correction, and the amount I needed. He also examined my trapezius botulinum toxin. He personally observed where my shoulders were tense and explained the procedure based on that. The filler was recommended at 30cc and the botulinum toxin was 100 units. Initially, he suggested trying 20cc and retouching, but since I was already doing it, I decided to go with 30cc. Then, when I showed him a photo of Jenny's shoulder, he decided to adjust it to 37cc. Before the procedure, he paid close attention to the line connecting my upper arm to my shoulder. I have some protruding skin on my upper arm, and he took that into account to design it so it blends naturally with my shoulder. I really liked that. The procedure was done under local anesthesia, with me sitting down and looking in the mirror. The filler was injected and the shape was constantly adjusted, so it felt like getting my hair done at a salon and checking the style right away. It was both novel and comforting. I had told the nurse in advance that I had low blood sugar and blood pressure, so I could faint if I was nervous. The nurse kept checking my condition and was very attentive, which made me feel a bit more at ease. My biggest worry was, "How much will it hurt?", but it was actually less painful than I expected. Maybe it's because the filler contains anesthetic, but I only felt a slight sting when I first received the local anesthesia. After that, it wasn't so painful that I was on edge until all 37cc were injected. The doctor also kept telling me, "Let me know if it hurts," which helped me relax a bit. The Botox was administered based on the areas I needed to work hard on, but I felt almost no pain in the trapezius muscle. In case you're wondering about the pain, here's a comparison based on what I've had in the past: Filler: Filler-dissolving injection (hyalase) > Nasolabial fold filler > Chin > Nose bridge = Shoulder filler. I remember it really hurting when I pressed down on my nasolabial fold and chin to shape them, but I can't really remember a moment where I went "ugh" like that with my shoulder. Botox: Nose tip > Forehead > Salivary gland > Trapezius > Glabella. I felt the most pain with forehead Botox, and the trapezius area was much more comfortable compared to that. I was a little anxious because I had to drive a long distance on the day of the procedure, but I didn't have any major issues even after driving for about 5 hours. I did feel a mild muscle pain for 2-3 days afterward. The swelling lasted for about 2 days, and my shoulder line looked slightly uneven, so I asked about it. They said it would smooth out over time, so I waited. Actually, by the fourth day, it was much smoother, and now it's the sixth day since the procedure, and the noticeable bumps are gone. I've always wanted square shoulders, so I've been stretching diligently and exercising, but I found my limits, perhaps due to my shoulder blades and body type. So, at one point, I was just giving up. But after getting shoulder filler, I feel like I've gotten rid of a complex I've had for a long time, and that's the biggest thing. Furthermore, shoulders aren't the first thing people notice, like the eyes and nose, so sometimes people don't sympathize with the concerns I have. That's why I felt like I was the only one worrying about them, but I feel relieved that I've been able to alleviate some of that. They say the effects of botox for the trapezius muscle take two to three weeks to become noticeable, so I'm waiting. Anyway, I've written down everything I can remember, in case you're curious about the details. I'm leaving this as a reference for anyone who, like me, has been constantly tinkering with retouching apps because of their shoulders.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been a while since I got shoulder filler, but I'm just starting to use it now, lol. My shoulder blades were really narrow to begin with, and they looked like they had a line on my thin shoulders? So when I wear clothes, they look like elementary school kids' clothes... I'm also on the thin side, so I don't have much fat, but my shoulders were sagging, making me look really flat and downcast. The term "coat hanger line" is exactly that... lol. But after I went to Hush Plastic Surgery and got the procedure done, the first thought that came to mind was, "Why did I only find out about this now...?" I hit the ground and regretted it... When I looked in the mirror right after the procedure, you could see that my shoulder line was completely smoothed out. When I straightened my shoulder, the line fell straight and felt like a right angle, so I was momentarily dazed, lol. It was really amazing. But it wasn't like, "My shoulders suddenly got wider! I got shoulders I never had!" It was more like, "They're slightly lifted up!" My original goal was to avoid looking like an elementary school student when I wore clothes, so... It wasn't just about pretty lines; I loved how the clothes looked so different. For those with similar concerns, it's good to know that this type of procedure exists. The pain... I was anesthetized, so it was bearable, but I was so nervous haha. My hands and feet are like ice... When I went into the operating room, the doctors and nurses kept talking to me, and they even offered me a candy if I felt dizzy or nervous. I forgot to eat one, but it really felt calmer. They kept telling me, "If you're feeling unwell, be sure to let me know," so I relaxed a lot. I can't remember how many times I thanked them on the way out... I felt so relieved. And my procedure was a little delayed on the day of the procedure. It's easy to get a little sensitive at times like this, but they explained the delay in advance, and the director personally apologized for making me wait, so I didn't feel any discomfort at all. Just a few words like these really matter. Since fillers fade over time, if I notice any noticeable signs of wear, I plan to go back for another injection. I trust both their skills and their service, so I've already made up my mind about that.

I guess I trusted them a little after hearing their explanation, lol. I set a surgery date right after the consultation. On the day of the procedure, they first designed the area, took photos, measured everything with a ruler, and then laid me down on the operating table... Strangely, I wasn't nervous at all. In the past, I felt empty without hip padding, so I always wore them, but now I can wear any clothes and they fit well, so that's the best. It's so convenient that I don't have to wear hip padding. Every time I looked in the mirror, I thought, "Oh, so that's why people do this..." lol. Maybe it's because the director explained everything so well from the consultation, but she was also so kind and thorough, which made me feel confident. So I set a date right away without hesitation. ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's already been a month since my surgery. Time really flies. LOL. These days, I'm just going about my daily life, and then suddenly, "Oh, right, I had surgery!" I had 200cc of Revoline filler at Hush. I was seriously considering fat grafting before the surgery, so I went to many consultations. I heard about the suction and grafting process, and I thought the recovery period would be a bit long, so I was a little hesitant. However, the filler didn't feel like it was too invasive, and the immediate post-op experience was more comfortable than I expected, which was the best part. If I'd had fat grafting back then, my recovery would have been different. For the first few days, I was even more cautious about sleeping. They told me not to sleep on my stomach, so I slept on my side. When I did sit, I placed a cushion under my thigh and tried my best to avoid putting pressure on the surgical site. Now, I'm just living my life as usual, except for one thing: I try not to get in any position that could cause the surgical site to bruise. Other than that, I don't think I'm particularly careful. I'm not very skinny, so my pelvic bone is particularly uneven, which always bothered me, but that wasn't the originally planned surgery area. Still, the director said a small amount of filler would make it look better, and he paid close attention to that detail. I was quite impressed. It felt like the doctor was examining every detail with great detail. Thanks to Director Jeong Young-chun, my overall silhouette feels smoother. Honestly, I was a little worried that filler might feel hard or like a foreign substance inside my body, but I didn't experience the discomfort I expected. Even though the amount wasn't much, it felt like a really good procedure. It felt natural, as if it were my own body. I was relieved that it wasn't the stuffy feeling I'd imagined before the surgery. And just like with the face, even a millimeter or centimeter difference can make a big difference in the body. The slight increase in the side pelvic line when viewed from the front is particularly noticeable. When I wear jeans or leggings, the lines are definitely different, so I end up taking full-body photos more often, and that's what I like the most every time I put on clothes. It just feels different when I look in the mirror haha. I think I'll probably go back to retouch once a year... It's because I trust them that they look at it with such detail.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: This is my review after completing my second retouch for shoulder filler. Honestly, the best part is that my upper arms aren't as prominent as before... That's a big deal, lol. The angles on my shoulders are more defined, so I feel like my overall lines are more balanced... Anyway, I like it. I was worried about the pain during the procedure, but it was so painless that it felt like I just lay down and came out. I was able to go about my daily life right away, so I didn't have to worry about needing to rest. The filler design was also designed so I didn't have to worry about the shape, because the doctor took care of it for me. That was the most comfortable part, lol. The swelling might make the shape look a little more puffy on the first or second day, so you might think, "Huh? Is it a bit high?" But considering that it'll go away, I think it's just the right amount. It settles naturally over time, and in photos, my shoulder line looks really pretty. I'm very satisfied.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: You know those scars from when you used to just pop your acne? I keep getting treatment for them, and this is my fifth time here. Haha. Every time I go, I think, "Why did I do that back then?" I've been to clinics that claim to be cheap and have a lot of customers and turn around quickly. It was so weird, the director didn't even speak to me, and they went straight into laser treatment without even looking at my face. After that experience, I realized it's better to pay a little more for a more thorough treatment. So now I go to a clinic that focuses solely on scars. At first, my skin felt more rejuvenated, and I wondered, "Is this right?" But after the last treatment, I definitely felt a difference. Every time I look in the mirror, I secretly think, "Huh? It seems a little better?" I don't know if it's dramatic or not, but it feels like I'm slowly starting to feel better with each treatment. She even went through the treatment plan step by step, which made me realize, "Wow, this isn't just a half-assed approach." Honestly, she said it would take a long time and the process wouldn't be easy, so I hesitated. But I was already feeling anxious, so I decided to take the plunge and get started. They were just expensive, and I didn't feel like I was being treated well. But I kept getting acne along the outer lines of my face. It got especially worse after summer, and I started seeing marks and scars forming. I figured no amount of home remedies would solve this, so I finally turned to laser treatment. This was my first time going to this clinic, so I was a bit skeptical. The consultation was incredibly detailed. They explained everything from where I was most concerned to the extent of my scars, which put me at ease. They weren't just like, "Here's a package," but rather, they explained in detail that I needed to first address my acne and then address my scars. This really helped me understand. They kept reminding me that scarring takes longer and costs more, so it's much better to treat it before it happens. уЕауЕа The more I listened, the more I realized what they meant, and I felt like all the time I'd wasted wasted. The procedure went more smoothly than I expected. I had it done somewhere else before and was worried because the redness lasted a long time, but here, there were no side effects like that. I didn't experience any discomfort afterward either. The price was surprisingly affordable for Gangnam, lol. I thought all the good places were expensive. Anyway, once a breakout occurs, the scars tend to last a long time, so I started here because I thought there would be no answer if I just left it alone. For now, I'm trying to calm my acne. I guess I'll have to take care of the scars later... They say it's cheaper and much easier to treat acne right away, so I think it's better to catch it in advance before I get mentally devastated like I did when I saw my scars. уЕауЕа

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I was so stressed out because of my acne scars... I couldn't stand it anymore, so I looked into dermatology. But since this place specializes in scars, I went in with an open mind. The thing that bothered me the most was the scar on my forehead that had been torn and tangled. That was the first thing I saw when I looked in the mirror... I felt like I was just being labeled as someone with a scar on their forehead. So, I started with a consultation to try and figure out what to do about it. When I got there, the hospital's entire system was centered around scars, and as they explained, I thought, "Wow, they've treated a ton of scars." However, they made it clear from the beginning that this wasn't a one-time visit, that I'd need multiple visits. I was a bit shocked when I first heard that... haha. The thought of how many times I'd need to come in kept swirling around in my head. But then they told me that the longer a scar has been there, the longer it takes to heal. Since it had already been a while, I automatically thought, "Oh, I should've come sooner..." For those of you with scars, I've heard that the longer you leave them, the longer you have to keep them. The director was also really attentive to the details, constantly checking in on my progress and explaining things to me. I was worried it might be a bit excessive, but the results were just right, which I'm very happy with. Anyway, I'm satisfied because my needs seem to have been met within the range I wanted, and if I ever get it done again, I think I'll come back here again.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I've always had this weird drooping of one side of my mouth when I smile or pronounce certain words... Whenever I take a picture, I always see that expression, and I look awkward for no reason. That was what bothered me the most. I thought it was just my facial expression, but during the consultation, the doctor told me that my lips were actually different lengths. Hearing that, I thought, "Oh, so that's why..." She explained that my lips are shorter than my eyes and nose, and that they were positioned on my face. She didn't just say, "Just fill it in here," but rather, she considered my lip shape and facial proportions and explained which direction the procedure should be done in, which was really nice. She also made my instructions very understandable. I had three procedures: lower lip lengthening, upper lip filler, and botox to the corners of my mouth. She told me beforehand that it would be difficult to achieve 100% asymmetry, but just slightly increasing the length of my lips and shifting the direction of the corners of my mouth made a huge difference. My mouth looked less stuffy than before, or maybe it felt more refreshed? Maybe that's why my round nose doesn't draw attention as much as it used to... I'm really satisfied with this. ЁЯе╣ The director explained that she could make my philtrum look shorter, but I told her that my philtrum is already quite short when I smile, and I really didn't like how my nose looked prominent. So I told her I wouldn't do that. When I told her what I didn't like, she took that into consideration, explaining why and how it would feel. The conversation was really nice. I think it would be better to think about what concerns you about your lips and facial proportions before you go, like I did. The nurses were also very kind and kept smiling while guiding me, so I didn't feel nervous, and the atmosphere was comfortable. It was a very cold day, so it was a bit far, so I lost some energy walking back and forth. Haha. Still, if I ever need another treatment, I'd love to go again. ЁЯШД

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been exactly four months since I had the surgery. These days, when I look in the mirror, the swelling has almost all gone down, so it looks exactly the way I wanted it to, and I think to myself, "It's okay~" lol. It was the same when I first went to Zero One Plastic Surgery for my consultation, and I ended up leaving it to Director Go Young-il, who did a lot of things at once. My eyes were a revision surgery, so I got natural adhesion and eye correction, as well as upper, lower, and lateral canthoplasty, which was a full package(?). I also had revision surgery on my nose, including the bridge, tip, and nasolabial angle, using donated costal cartilage. For my face, I had liposuction for cheeks, a double chin, and a jawline, and I also had thread lifting. It looks like a lot when I write it down, but I did it all at once... lol. Now, most of the swelling has gone down, so it looks natural and doesn't feel awkward. I think it turned out well, so I'm quite satisfied with it.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been a little over two months since my surgery, and I'm amazed at how different I feel when I look in the mirror these days. At Zero One, I had a double chin, a lower chin, liposuction, fat grafting, and thread lifting all in one procedure with Director Ko Young-il. At some point, when I look at my profile, my double chin no longer looks as sagging as it used to, but my jawline looks much lighter. When I look at my face from the front, my face looks slimmer overall, too, so I tend to take a lot of side-view photos. Regarding my eyes... the tuck effect is definitely noticeable. Remember how stuffy and obscured my pupils were before? Now that's gone, my pupils look more open and clear. They say my face looks softer and more defined than before. Maybe because I also had facial fat grafting, my cheeks and cheekbones look more natural and fuller than before, without the sunken look that comes with losing weight. Even up close, it barely looks awkward. When I meet close friends, they say that although it doesn't seem like anything has changed, my impression looks really sophisticated, and my face really looks smaller, so just hearing that makes me feel good. They said that it's only been two months so it hasn't completely settled in, but the swelling has already gone down a lot and it looks natural, so I'm just quietly waiting to see how it will settle in as time goes by.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been a little over two months since my surgery, and these days, whenever I look in the mirror, I feel a strange sense of joy. Even while washing my face, I take another look... Why am I like this? Haha. I had a buried eye procedure, a functional nose job with three types of surgery, a bulbous nose, a nasal tip correction, deep cheekbones, double chin liposuction, and thread lifting all in one. It was a full course that was suffocating, but now that the swelling has almost gone down, I don't have any inconveniences in my daily life. My stuffy nose is gone, and I don't feel like there's anything stuck in my nose. The funny thing is, I used to work as an assistant on the surgical team, so I know pretty well what kind of surgeon I am. That's why I wanted to get my surgery from Dr. Ko from the beginning. He's meticulous, and he's not just someone who looks like they've had plastic surgery, but someone who designs the entire face to harmonize with it. I know that better than anyone else. Haha. Everyone around me says the same thing. My eyes and nose both turned out really well. People say they wouldn't know I had surgery if I didn't tell them. They say it looks natural, like it was my natural face... These days, the things I hear the most are things like, "It looks like it was done just for you." Anyway, these days, I'm at the point where I secretly feel proud when I wash my face or see my face reflected in a window as I pass by, so I take a second look... haha

I don't usually write things like this... but I was so shocked when I saw my mom;; First of all, I didn't think I would notice much of a difference since I see her face every day? The director's name was Director Ko Young-il, and I thought he'd do a good job on my face too... I tried to believe him. In fact, the reason I found out about this place was thanks to my mom's friend's daughter. The results of his surgery were so natural and good, so my mom asked, "Where is that place?" and we went together... My mom is very picky about things like that, so it was even more surprising. When I first went into the hospital, they said it had only recently opened, so maybe that's why the facilities felt like a new building and were very clean overall. I still remember how the moment I opened the door and walked in, the scent was nice. It didn't have that typical hospital smell, but a scent that just made me feel good? That's it. The process just went straight through. First, I took a picture, talked to the head of the counseling room, and then went in for a consultation with the director, almost without waiting. What was unusual was that there was no separate consultation fee? This was pretty good. My mom was originally worried about the dark circles under her eyes and the uneven lines on her face. She hated hearing things like she looked fierce or cold when she had no expression, so she said this many times, тАЬI really donтАЩt want to have a blank, angular face like a witch.тАЭ After listening to all that, the director said that we should fix the sagging under her eyes with lower eyelid surgery and smooth out the dark areas and uneven lines with fat grafting. He looked at the sunken cheeks next to her mouth, the nasolabial folds, the temples, and even the jawline, and explained how to achieve an overall balance. My mom has a bit of cheekbones, so the director pointed that out too much pressure could make her cheekbones look more prominent, so he explained that we should adjust the intensity accordingly. We also did thread lifting, which was what my mom was most afraid of. She kept asking, тАЬWill it leave marks like bumps on a mole?тАЭ But the director explained it well, talking about Silhouette Soft, and it helped ease those worries. She said that it was a way to correct sagging in a natural way, and that it wouldn't be a weird style like before, which reassured my mom. The exact style she wanted was "a natural, youthful look without any obvious signs of surgery." So I think it was a good idea to do it together with fat grafting. My mom kept looking in the mirror and laughing to herself after seeing the results. I was watching from the side and thought, "Wow, just fat grafting can make such a difference." Anyway, my mom looks so pretty overall that if someone saw me and said I was her aunt, they would believe me, so I'm excited too.

I was constantly concerned about my sagging cheeks and jawline, so I kept getting them, but I didn't feel any noticeable changes... I was wondering if this was the right thing to do, but then I heard that liposuction and lifting together are good, so I looked around for a hospital and decided on this one. During the surgery, the director checked and examined even the smallest areas of concern that I hadn't even mentioned, which was impressive. The liposuction seemed to be thoroughly done, even to the double chin area, as the cheeks and deep cheeks felt heavy. It seems like the liposuction was done thoroughly. There's still some swelling, so I need to wait and see, but I can already see a difference in the sagging cheeks and overall jawline. I have a feeling it'll look even cleaner once the swelling goes down. The double chin and deep cheeks that were heavy have been smoothed out, so I'm curious to see what happens in a month... Haha, I think they did a very thorough job this time, so I plan to go to Irock again later and get additional thread lifting done.

LOL It's only been a month since the surgery, so there's still some swelling, but I'm very satisfied. The nurse said my swelling was on the low side. The aftercare was really thorough, even with the high frequency, and the feeling of being taken care of was amazing... This was more helpful than I thought. I've heard a lot that the director is good at eye surgeries, and he's also really good at liposuction... I thought that's why everyone comes to him. Anyway, I'm very satisfied, so I'm leaving this review. LOL

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I went to Zero One because of my face and eyes. I had eye revision surgery (natural adhesion + upper lip lift), facial liposuction (cheeks + double chin + jawline) + thread lifting all at once with Director Go Young-il. I had double eyelid surgery with natural adhesion at another hospital 10 years ago, but as time passed, one side came loose a little... When I put on eye makeup, the size difference between the two sides is really visible уЕа On top of that, as I'm in my 40s, you can clearly see that my cheekbones are sagging, so every morning when I look in the mirror, I feel bad for no reason... I was always worried about my age, so I had some time and decided to do it right, so I searched for eye revision surgery like crazy уЕЛуЕЛ I looked up a ton of reviews, compared them here and there, and since it was a one-person hospital, I found that Zero One had good reviews for eye revision surgery. I made a reservation over the phone and went for a consultation, and seeing how they drew my line during the consultation made my mind up right away. When I told them which part of my face I was most concerned about, they pointed out exactly that point and understood the look I wanted. I was going to just do my eyes, but they said they would do jawline liposuction and thread lifting together, so I set the surgery date right then and there. It's been about two weeks since the surgery, and the swelling in my eyes is still going down, but when I look in the mirror, the left and right sides look the same, so that seems okay. The jawline is really... I was satisfied from the moment I took off the band. I didn't expect much because I have a bit of fat on my face, but my face line looks slimmer, and the sagging of my cheekbones, which I was concerned about, is gone, which was the best part. I made a reservation at the hospital in advance, so I hardly had to wait, and the staff were all friendly, so when people ask me about this, I just tell them that I went to Zero One.

But this time, I was surprised to be called in almost immediately, almost without waiting. The atmosphere felt much more relaxed than the last time I went. The people at the desk and the guides were all friendly and explained everything well, so I didn't have a chance to be nervous. The doctor kept smiling and talking to me throughout the procedure, which helped me relax a bit. When I was trembling in pain, he kept saying, "Just hold on a little longer," and soothing me... But seriously... what can I say... it really hurt. уЕа Tears weren't just streaming down my face, they were streaming down my face... It was so painful that I practically burst into tears. I was in so much pain that the doctor suddenly put a doll in my hand and told me to hold on tightly. He also brought me tissues to wipe my tears. He also kept asking if I was okay and trying to comfort me, which was embarrassing but also somewhat comforting. It feels a bit like a capital T (?), but it's also funny because they take care of it in the meantime... haha. But since I had a rough idea when I first got it, I knew it would hurt this much, and it was within that range, so I just thought, 'Okay, this is enough' and left. I'm still thinking about whether I should go again in a month or not.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I didn't want to get a nose job right away, but I always wanted a more defined nose bridge. As I looked around, I kept noticing people with pretty nose bridges... So I decided to do some proper research and compared hospitals until I finally decided on ALU Plastic Surgery. I had silicone implants for the bridge, autologous costal cartilage for the tip, and even had a rhinoplasty. It's been a little less than a month now, and it's amazing how much swelling I see in the mirror these days. When I first got my cast off, a week or two later, I actually thought, "Huh? This is fine!" Even then, considering the swelling, I was quite pleased with the shape of the tip and bridge. Now, after a month, the lines seem to be settling much more naturally. My nose bridge is also gradually taking shape, just like I envisioned, so I keep looking at it to myself. It's not completely finished yet; my philtrum feels slightly pulled in, and there's still some swelling around the osteotomy. So, I'm secretly looking forward to seeing how it changes as it gets thinner. When I went for my one-month checkup, Director Kim Hyun-joo told me that the swelling was going down well, which reassured me. I still have a bit of scarring near the entrance of my nostril, but since it's only been a month since the surgery, she said it will get better with time. She also said that if it's still the same at my three-month checkup, they'll look into it with laser then. She checked each of these things and explained them calmly, so I felt like she was paying close attention every time I visited.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been about two months, so I'm finally starting to feel better, so I'm going to write this down. These days, whenever I look in the mirror, the first thing I see is my profile and my eyes, and that used to be the most stressful part. My double eyelids are thin, so if you look straight on, it's okay, but if you turn your head slightly, the angle of my nose is so obvious, so I always had to be careful about the angle when taking pictures. But it took a long time to decide on the surgery... I watched YouTube reviews until I was sick of them, and I spent weeks comparing hospital reviews and before-and-after photos. Then, I kept seeing cases by Dr. Kim Hyun-joo of ALU Plastic Surgery, so I decided to have her do both my eyes and nose. My nose was done using autologous costal cartilage and silicone, and my eyes were done with a non-incision double eyelid surgery. Immediately after the surgery, it wasn't just swelling and pain that bothered me; I was also concerned about my nose and eyes. Even the smallest changes can make you anxious. Every time I asked about this and that, the director immediately confirmed with the director and explained it to me, which was a huge comfort. I had a lot of worries even though everything was fine, but thanks to them answering every single one of them, I was able to recover with peace of mind. Now, the swelling has gone down a lot, and the reactions of people around me have definitely changed. In the past, people would say things like, "Do you really need to get it done?" But these days, people often tell me my side profile looks more refined, my eyes are clearer, and I'm pretty. I also often hear that my overall facial expression has brightened. Every time I hear those words, I think, "Oh, I made the right decision to get the surgery without hesitation. I also like it more and more when I look at myself, and my confidence has definitely increased.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been three months, so I'm feeling a bit more settled now, so I'm writing this. My nose was originally a bit low, so I wasn't particularly happy with the profile line. So, I had high-quality cartilage and filler before, but as time went on, the jumble of options became more and more confusing, so I decided to get it done properly with autologous rib cartilage. Then, while browsing Instagram, the algorithm kept popping up posts about ALU Plastic Surgery, so I clicked on it out of boredom. After seeing the before-and-after photos and explanations of Dr. Kim Hyun-joo's surgery, I thought, "This is it!" The way she treated the bridge of the nose and the bridge of the nose perfectly suited my style, so I made a consultation right away. I mentioned my previous high-quality cartilage and filler, and they removed the high-quality threads during the surgery. They also injected hyaluronic acid beforehand to smooth out the filler. The surgery involved using autologous rib cartilage to elevate the tip of the nose, silicone injections into the bridge, and even a nasolabial fold and a bulbous nose correction, all in one procedure. People around me often tell me things like, "Your nose looks pretty," and that makes me feel good, lol. What I especially like the most is how three-dimensional it looks from the side. Maybe it's because they've done a lot of revision surgeries at the hospital from the beginning, but even though it was my first rhinoplasty, it feels like they did a really detailed job that fit my face? It's only been three months so it's not completely over yet, but my low nose tip and my side profile, which were the most stressful parts before the surgery, now look a lot more three-dimensional, so I'm really satisfied with my current condition.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: Let's start with rhinoplasty and double eyelid surgery, but lol. There are so many reviews of men's noses these days. I had some free time during my final year vacation, so I just kept searching. Whenever I looked at a map of plastic surgery clinics in Gangnam, red dots would pop up like crazy, driving me crazy. Meanwhile, while looking at photos, I saw one that really hit me: "This is it." It was ALU Plastic Surgery. After scrolling through other reviews, I realized it was similar to what I was envisioning, so I immediately scheduled a consultation. I'd actually been to four different clinics for consultations... (I lost 120,000 won in consultation fees alone...) But strangely, the one I chose last has always stuck with me. ALU Plastic Surgery was the last one I considered, and I think I had my heart set on it even before I went there. My nose has always been in poor condition, so I'm extremely sensitive to rhinitis and side effects. So when I was looking into surgery, I never had the mindset of "just looking pretty is enough." I looked up Dr. Kim Hyun-joo and found that she uses autologous costal cartilage, and that she places great importance on maintaining a strong and stable nose, not just the shape. I binge-watched her website and her YouTube videos, and her surgical philosophyтАФor should I say, her approachтАФwas completely aligned with my goals. Watching her practically solidified my mind. What was interesting was that when I went for my consultation, I noticed that most hospitals have staff take photos, but here, the director herself was holding a pad and taking photos for me. At that moment, I felt reassured. She also looked at my facial features and characteristics, explaining in great detail what kind of lines would suit me and how to perform my nose. As I listened, I had more questions. But she kept asking, "Do you have any questions?" I was able to open up about everything without worrying about what others might think. Rhinitis, concerns about the shape being distorted, side effects, things like that. If you're planning a consultation, write down your questions like crazy and ask them. She'll answer them all, really. It would take a long time to describe the hospital atmosphere and the kindness of the directors, but I think you'll feel it better when you go there in person, so I won't go into detail. It's not just a place that smells like money, but because it's a one-person hospital, it feels like they treat each and every patient as a real person, and that's what I liked. Oh, right, after I was discharged from the military, I thought of it as a gift to myself and got non-incision double eyelid surgery and a nose job at the same time. Now, both my nose line and eye line are similar to the shapes I used to think "I wish I had this" when I looked at photos, so I'm satisfied with that part as well.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been a while since I had all my implants removed, and since it's been about two months since I had my reconstructive rhinoplasty, I'm going to write about it. I was going to talk about it in order, but as I was writing, I'll just write whatever comes to mind, lol. First, I had my nose completely reconstructed by Dr. Kim Hyun-joo using autologous tissue. The bridge of my nose was done with scalp fascia and autologous ribs, and the tip was also done with autologous ribs. I even went in with plans for columella reconstruction and short nose correction. I was told extensively during my consultation that this clinic primarily uses autologous tissue. But the journey to get here was quite lengthy... At first, I had cosmetic rhinoplasty at another major hospital, but one day, I looked in the mirror and saw what looked like white silicone reflections on the tip of my nose. At first, I wondered if I was being overly sensitive, but it kept bothering me, so I searched extensively for information on reconstructive rhinoplasty. After reading reviews, I came across a lot of posts about RU Plastic Surgery, so I finally made the effort and went for a consultation. Honestly, I wish I hadn't had the reconstructive rhinoplasty... ' That was my thought, but after the consultation, they said that I would get a contracted nose. уЕа They also said that the skin at the tip of my nose was so thin that the silicone could come out... In order to recover the tissue with stem cells, the protruding implants had to be removed first, so I had all of them removed right away after the consultation. After the implants were removed, it was even harder because I had to keep going for stem cell treatments almost every two weeks. I kept going back and forth to the hospital... уЕа But after going through that process, about four months after the removal, I had a contracted nose revision surgery. In the meantime, my mental state had calmed down a bit, and my nose felt like it had recovered to some extent, so I thought, 'Let's just do it.' To be honest, there were a lot of uncomfortable things right after the surgery. It felt tight where the costal cartilage was taken, and I was constantly conscious of the incision above my hairline because of the scalp fascia... It bothered me every time I put my hair up. But as time went by, I felt it less and less, and my thoughts changed from being bothersome to thinking, 'Oh, it was good that I got it done.' The thing that stressed me out the most was the combination of my short, upturned nose and bulbous nose. Since I often interact with people, I really hated having my nostrils visible from the front. Now that I've gotten used to seeing them from the front, I'm most comfortable with that, and I especially like the side profile so much that sometimes I can't even remember what my old nose looked like. уЕОуЕО I have thick skin to begin with, so I'm 100% satisfied with the front view! I'm not at that point yet, but in my daily life, I'm almost always intimidated by my nose and I walk around confidently. When I look at pictures taken from the side, I think I look prettier now than when I first got it done... I kind of think that way. уЕа

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been a little over two months, and I'm starting to write my review now. The order might be a bit confusing, but I'll just write whatever comes to mind. First, I was recommended costal cartilage for my nose bridge... but for some reason, I felt a bit reluctant about it. уЕауЕа After much deliberation, I ended up going with silicone. I was worried about contractures with silicone, so I asked about it, and they said they could reinforce it with fascia, so I went with that. The director said my case wasn't severely inflamed or severely contracted due to the silicone, so the silicone could be reused. It was a slightly distorted contracture, but not a severe case. Actually, the reason I chose the clinic was even funnier: an acquaintance of mine had a revision rhinoplasty at ALU Plastic Surgery. Her nose was so similar to the style I like. After seeing her in person, I immediately looked into ALU and scheduled a consultation with Director Kim Hyun-joo. Since revision rhinoplasty was something I'd been wanting for a long time, I was extra cautious. Before the surgery, I frantically collected photos and references of the nose I wanted and even printed them out. It wasn't just a demonstration; I kept emphasizing, "This look is really important!" lol. That's probably why they hung those photos in the operating room before the surgery. If you find this important, you might want to refer to them. It's been a little over two months since my surgery, and the initial swelling, which was dull and puffy, has gone down a lot. When I look in the mirror, it's definitely less rounded and more slender. By my standards, it's finally starting to look like my own... The area where the costal cartilage was removed is still a bit redder than I expected, so I'm consistently applying scar ointment. I think this will take a bit more time. But the most important thing is that the shape of my nose is almost exactly what I envisioned, which is what I'm most satisfied with. Many people around me have been asking, "Did you get your nose done again?" They've also asked me where I got it done, and when I told them where, quite a few of my friends have gone after hearing my story. People tell me that it suits my face well, and I feel proud whenever I hear that. Haha. Oh, I can't help but talk about my consultation style... Director Kim Hyun-joo gives very thorough consultations, so I think it's perfect for people who have a lot of questions. I heard a lot about revision rhinoplasty and short nose surgery, and I understood it well because it felt like she explained everything in detail. I've gained a lot of trust in that area.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been about six months, so I'm finally getting used to it, so I'll write about it. These days, I hardly ever feel short of breath, so sometimes the first thing that comes to my mind is, "Oh, I had surgery!" lol. Maybe it's because my septum deviation and inferior turbinate were also addressed, but compared to before, my breathing space definitely feels wider? I tried not to get my hopes up too much because they said rhinitis could recur at any time, but I'm really satisfied so far. My nose originally looked a bit blunt and bulbous when viewed from the front, but from the side, it had a beak-like protrusion and a slightly droopy tip, so I always got annoyed when taking pictures. I kept worrying about it, but in the end, I decided to get my own costal cartilage done at ALU Plastic Surgery. I thought I'd get both functional and cosmetic surgery done, so I went with a functional and cosmetic nose. When I first had my consultation, the director and the head of the department explained things so calmly that I felt like I could trust them. Regarding the actual cost, they helped me a lot and took care of everything, so my anxiety in that area has greatly decreased. I had the surgery with osteotomy and bulbous nose correction, and at first, I couldn't tell because of the swelling, but as time went by, I could see the change in shape, especially from the front. Now, it's not a nose that's too obvious, but it's more natural and has a bit of a sophisticated feel. Every time I went for a follow-up, Director Kim Hyun-joo and the director calmly answered all my questions without being annoyed, so I felt at ease as I continued going. People around me were jealous and said I was lucky to have this result after my first nose job. I heard that many people go for revision surgery, so I was a little worried, but I'm most relieved that my nose turned out the way I wanted it the first time.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been three months, so I think it's worth writing a review, so I'm writing this. уЕОуЕО First of all, I'm enjoying shading my nose when I put on makeup... In the past, my nose tip and width looked so spread out that shading didn't show, right? But these days, I can really see the difference in the width of my nose tip even when I look at it from the front, so I end up taking a second look every time I put on makeup. уЕЛуЕЛ I used to have a bulbous nose, so I was a bit stressed out, but I asked a friend who knows a lot about plastic surgery/procedures. She told me that my face couldn't be fixed with high nose or fillers... ^^ So I just kept thinking, 'Oh, I should get surgery someday,' but then she got it first. It was just my nose, but my overall impression became so soft and pretty, and that made me feel more certain. So I went to the same ALU Plastic Surgery Clinic for a consultation. During the consultation, the director turned on a PPT and explained the surgical method, the size of the rib cage scar, the pros and cons, and even before-and-after photos of similar cases, which made it easier to understand than I thought. My columella tends to be turned inward, so my mouth didn't look as pretty. They said that tightening the columella and adjusting the nasolabial angle would make it look much more harmonious, so they addressed that as well. The CT scan showed that my nasal septum cartilage was a bit small, and they didn't have the necessary amount for a bulbous nose job. They told me I'd have to choose between autologous ribs and donated ribs. They said a bulbous nose requires a lot of firm cartilage... They said autologous ribs are better for raising and narrowing the tip of the nose, so I went with autologous ribs. I was really worried about the scar, but when I went for the follow-up, they said the scars were fine and well-positioned, so I didn't need laser treatment. That was such a relief... haha. What I liked about LU was that the director in charge kindly guided me through the entire preparation process, which put my nerves at ease. After the surgery, Director Kim Hyun-joo personally checked on me during treatment, disinfection, and follow-up visits. Knowing that they'd be able to detect any inflammation or side effects immediately put me at ease. Of course, there was one difficult point... When they took out the stitches in the first week, it was just... so painful уЕауЕа At that time, I really cried and thought, 'Why did I do it...? ', but once I got over that, it was okay. In the beginning of the surgery, when you look at the front, my nose looked a little thick, but after about 3 months, the swelling, or should I say, that started to go down and the shape seemed to settle much more naturally? So these days, my satisfaction with the front view has definitely increased. Thinking back, I've been worried for years about my floppy nose, but in the end, getting the autologous rib implant here was a pretty good choice. It's not completely final, so I'll have to wait and see how it goes, but these days, whenever I look in the mirror, I can't really think about the past. уЕОуЕО

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I was just counting the days and realized it's already been 189 days since my rhinoplasty revision. I was looking at the calendar and was like, "Huh? It's like this?" haha. Actually, I wasn't considering revision surgery from the beginning. One day, I was a bit stunned when I saw a photo. When I looked in the mirror, it looked normal, but in photos, my nose looked slightly upturned, and it became more and more noticeable as time went on. It wasn't noticeable when I smiled, so I thought, "Is it okay?" But in photos, it was so obvious that I started thinking about revision surgery. There were three main things I wanted: I wanted the tip of my nose to be visible from the front and the upturned appearance from the side. I wanted the bridge to look natural enough to be unnoticeable, but the tip to look rounder. And most importantly, I wanted my nose to look natural overall, so that people wouldn't immediately say, "I had plastic surgery." While researching hospitals, I looked up reviews of revision rhinoplasty surgeries and found ALU Plastic Surgery, so I had a consultation. At first, I was just going to get a consultation, but after my consultation with Dr. Kim Hyun-joo, I immediately thought, "Ah, I need to get this done quickly before spring comes." So, I immediately scheduled my revision surgery for a month later. Before the surgery, I also received stem cell therapy once a week. The surgery was entirely autologous. I used my own ribs to create a bridge for my nose (using both minced costal cartilage and temporal fascia), lifted the tip of my nose, and even had a reconstructed nose, a nasolabial angle, and a crooked nose. Just hearing the names of the procedures made me feel like I'd done everything. But honestly, what scared me the most wasn't the actual surgery itself, but the general anesthesia. I was worried I'd wake up feeling nauseous or limp. I heard the surgery took about three and a half hours, and the first day of the rib removal was better than I expected. In fact, the side where my temporal fascia was removed was more sore and uncomfortable. Perhaps because it was entirely autologous, the swelling and bruising seemed to last a while. At first, the shape of my nose bridge felt a bit like an avatar, and I was especially concerned about the bruising on the tip, but now the bruising has completely gone down and I don't feel that way at all. Until six months ago, I was a little worried because my nose tip was plump, thinking, "It won't settle in like this..." But these days, the swelling has gone down and the shape is gradually becoming more natural, so it's okay. It hasn't even been a year yet, so I think it will settle in more in the future. I trusted Director Kim Hyun-joo and chose the revision surgery, so I have no regrets or concerns. I'm currently satisfied with my current condition.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: I'm in my 4th month of revision rhinoplasty. уЕЛуЕЛ Thinking back, before the surgery, all I thought was, 'Will this really go down well?' But looking back, I laugh at myself for worrying so much back then... Fortunately, the shape and positioning feel much more natural than I had worried, so I'm really relieved... уЕОуЕО But since the entire nose bridge was raised with autologous costal cartilage, the swelling seems to last quite a while. I thought the major swelling would go away after about a month, right? But 2 months and now 4 months are different... When I look in the mirror, I'm like, "Huh? It went down again?" So I can still feel it changing little by little. It's not completely gone down, but I think the swelling is going down slightly. You know, what happens after the surgery is more important than the surgery itself... Maybe because RU does a lot of revision rhinoplasty, their aftercare feels really thorough. Every time I went for a follow-up, they would immediately give me an injection if there was any ambiguous scar tissue, and they told me in advance that they could consider laser treatment if needed, which put me at ease. Usually, after the surgery, they just say, "Everything went well!" But when I had surgery somewhere else almost 10 years ago, I remember how difficult it was to see the director's face after the surgery, so I felt it even more deeply. My nose was upturned, and I also had capsular contracture from the silicone, so I was a bit mentally unstable. So, when I went to ALU Plastic Surgery, I asked a lot of detailed questions, and the director explained everything in a very practical way, which was very helpful. Instead of just giving me perfunctory comments, he explained why I needed to do it this way and what my condition was like. The tone was different from other consultations I've had at other hospitals, so that's what I remember. The hospital atmosphere wasn't at all tense, and the directors and staff were all soft-spoken and kind, so I felt comfortable asking them about various things. Oh, and for those who are curious about the ingredients, I'll write this down. I had stem cell treatment twice, and for the bridge of my nose, they used scalp fascia and minced costal cartilage, and for the tip of my nose, they only used costal cartilage. I think you can think of it like this.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: After my military discharge and preparing to return to school, the first thing I did was get a nose consultation. I'd heard so much about noses from people around me, lol. "You only need a nose~"тАФI'd hear things like that so often that even though I tried not to, I couldn't stop thinking about it. I'd keep imagining things like, "I wish my nostrils weren't visible from the front, I wish my nose was a little higher and more natural..." Actually, what bothered me the most was the side profile. When viewed from the side, my nose looked slightly upturned. Maybe that's why I always thought my nose looked really hollow in photos. Whenever I looked at selfies, I would zoom in on my nose for no reason, lol. But what I was most afraid of was a second surgery. I really didn't want to get it done again, so I only looked for options with fewer side effects and less noticeable changes. So I consulted with quite a few different hospitals, and ultimately, I ended up going to YU Plastic Surgery because... they were the most persistent in explaining things. It wasn't just, "I'll do it this way~". Director Kim Hyun-joo personally explained the autologous rib rhinoplasty process, what goes into my nose, and why this plan was necessary, using a PPT. I realized that this wasn't something I could just memorize and say. That's why I decided to have my first nose job with Director Kim Hyun-joo. The plan was to use costal cartilage for the tip of the nose, silicone implants for the bridge, and we'd also do osteotomy, a bulbous nose correction, a short nose correction, and a nasolabial angle correction. This was all planned after I was discharged from the military, so it felt like a life event... haha. The first week after the surgery was tough. Breathing was very difficult, so sleeping and moving around were quite difficult. But after the cast was removed in the first week and the second week passed, breathing became much easier. The swelling went down faster than I expected, so I didn't have much trouble going out. Now that I'm back in college, I meet a lot of new people, and it seems like no one has ever guessed I had a nose job. There's no mention of "Did you get plastic surgery?" and people just think that's just how my nose is. But it doesn't feel ordinary either. By my standards, it's the right height and pretty shape, but it's amazing because it's not noticeable. I'm still satisfied with my choice of autologous rib at ALU.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: This is already my third nose job... I thought this would be the last time, so I had a revision at LU уЕЛуЕЛ It's been about two weeks since my surgery, and the shape of my nose is so different than I thought, so I'm just drawing it out... My nose is originally quite small, so I thought it wouldn't grow with something soft. Before that, I researched a lot of different options... I had my first surgery at OO Plastic Surgery in the countryside, and they did ear cartilage + silicone implants. But when I actually saw the results, I was like, "Huh...?"... It wasn't my style at all, so I was completely dissatisfied уЕа Then, for my second surgery, I went to OO Plastic Surgery, which is famous for its dermis, and had a revision surgery with buttock dermis + ear cartilage. I thought, "It'll be okay this time," but the line wasn't what I imagined... The bridge of my nose felt a bit sunken, so I later had Juvederm filler filler on the bridge of my nose. But that too... didn't make a big difference. After doing this, I really felt the limitations of using these soft materials to grow my nose... lol. So I started searching mainly on using autologous costal cartilage for both the tip and the bridge of the nose. During that process, I read a lot of reviews of Director Kim Hyun-joo, and among the cases of reconstructed nose surgery, there was someone who had a nose job that was really similar to my previous nose condition. I saw the picture and immediately applied for a consultation lol. When I consulted with the director, I asked, "Do I have a contracted nose...?" and she said it wasn't serious enough to actually be considered a reconstructed nose surgery. She said there was no inflammation, so that was really fortunate уЕауЕа But since she handles a lot of reconstructed nose cases, I had expectations like, "Wow, with this much, maybe she can make my small nose a bit straighter?" And during the consultation, she said she would raise it as much as possible, so I was tempted by those words... The tip of the nose was done with autologous costal cartilage, and the bridge of the nose was made by inserting minced autologous rib into the scalp fascia and inserting it like an autologous tissue implant. I had a short nose correction, a crooked nose correction that you can see from the front, and a columella lowering done at the same timeтАж The price was exactly as IтАЩd heardтАж lol. But now, after two weeks, when I look in the mirror, my nose is much higher than I thought, so it still feels a bit awkward and strange. I really wonder how the shape of my nose can change so much in just a few daysтАж In person, my nose is still swollen, so it looks really puffy. Still, the height and overall size have grown, so considering that I had it done twice at other hospitals and kept thinking, тАЬOh, this isnтАЩt itтАжтАЭ, IтАЩm glad I chose this one. IтАЩve also heard a lot that RLтАЩs after-sales service and care are good, so I feel a bit less anxious if something happens. Of course, the thought of going under the knife again is terrifyingтАж For now, IтАЩm super satisfied, so if youтАЩre looking into revision rhinoplasty, I think it would be worth getting a consultation.
