ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been a little over two months since my surgery. I had a short nose, which is kind of ambiguous, but I went to see Dr. Kim Hyun-joo at RYU. I didn't have a huge complex about my nose, but I always felt like there was something missing in the center of my face. It was short and small, and the center looked slightly sunken, so I always felt like I looked boring in photos. Then, when an acquaintance of mine got rhinoplasty, I was shocked by how completely transformed her entire appearance was. From then on, I became obsessed with it and started researching. I downloaded a plastic surgery app, looked at reviews and before-and-after photos, and went to three or four places for consultations. The RYU before-and-after photos were the closest to what I had in mind. They weren't overly raised, and had a natural, straight look. During the consultation, Dr. Kim Hyun-joo told me she immediately grasped my points, which reassured me. Even when I vaguely described the image I wanted, she would say, "Oh, that's what you mean?" and point it out, which was a huge plus. When I was consulting with other hospitals, they told me that because my nose was short and the columella was set back, autologous rib grafting was almost essential for rhinoplasty. They said costal cartilage would be used in all three areas, so I was somewhat prepared to accept the possibility of scarring. So, the final plan I received at RU included costal cartilage for the tip, silicone for the bridge, and even columella and short nose correction. Honestly, the estimate was the most expensive of all the hospitals I consulted with. However, I had the most time to see the director in person after the surgery, and I felt like I'd be able to continue receiving care if any issues arose, so I decided to go there. The director in charge was also very kind and helpful, explaining everything in detail. Immediately after the surgery... it was more painful than I expected. The area where the costal cartilage was removed was particularly sore, and my nose was stuffed with cotton, making breathing difficult and my mouth very dry. Shortly after returning home, my throat started to hurt. It was almost like the stinging pain you get when you swallow when you have tonsillitis. It turned out that it was caused by a tube being inserted into your throat during general anesthesia. The pain lasted for about three days, but after that, it subsided to the point where it only hurt when you strained. I was able to go about my daily life cautiously. The bruising lasted longer than I expected. It was widespread at first, and I think the yellow bruises remained for about two weeks. Still, I went to the hospital the day after the surgery, the first week, and the second week, and the director would check on me in person, or the nurse would treat it first, and then the director would check on me again. I wasn't anxious at all. Now, I'm two months in, and the swelling has gone down a lot. My nose is settling into the straight shape I imaginedтАФa natural, straight line, not a sharp point.

First of all, I like the shape of my nose the most because it has the "round nose tip" feel I wanted. Not a pointy or sharp tip, but a natural, round tip. My first nose job was without implants and only had the tip done. Even then, my mouth looked a bit protruding, so I expected that if I just raised the tip of my nose nicely, it would look less prominent. But right after the surgery, I kept thinking, "Huh? Is this right?" уЕа As time went by, my nose tip got lower and thinner, so I was really disappointed with the final shape. I'm in an ambiguous state, not sure if this is an improvement... So I kept thinking that I should get another surgery someday, and since I happened to have a vacation this time, I started looking into it properly. While researching several hospitals, I came across reviews of ALU Plastic Surgery. The nose line in the photo was exactly my style, and seeing that it was a single-director clinic specializing in autologous rib cartilage surgery gave me a sense of trust. I thought it would be better to have one director review all my cases rather than having to rotate through several. During my consultation, the doctor explained almost exactly what I had in mind, which was a big factor. So, I immediately booked an autologous rib cartilage revision surgery with Dr. Kim Hyun-joo. Honestly, what I was most worried about was the rib removal. I'd heard stories of severe chest pain and difficulty breathing, so I was a bit intimidated. Surprisingly, my condition was much less severe than my first surgery, when I only used septal cartilage. It was really painful when I bent over or made strenuous movements, and I thought, "Oh, that's the pain..." уЕа But after about three days, it felt like just severe muscle pain. It wasn't completely painless, but it was more bearable than I had feared. The nasolabial fold correction was also included, which was quite surprising. At first, I looked in the mirror and thought, "Oh, is it just my imagination?" But as time went by, I could feel my mouth protruding a lot less. The protruding feeling is less noticeable. The tip of my nose has also become higher than before, so my overall impression feels much softer. These days, whenever I take a picture, I'm constantly amazed, thinking, "Wow, just one nose can make such a difference in an image!" Haha. And whenever I go for a checkup, Director Kim Hyun-joo really checks everything thoroughly, which makes me feel at ease. ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: When I first decided to have surgery, I was concerned about the shape of my nose, but when I got a CT scan at the hospital, they told me they needed to address functional aspects as well as cosmetic ones. So, I decided to get it all done in one go and went with functional rhinoplasty at ALU Plastic Surgery. I've always been passionate about a perfectly straight nose line... So, during my consultation, we talked about autologous costal cartilage and silicone implants, and that's how I went about it. The reason I got the surgery was that the tip of my nose was slightly droopy and rounded, so I felt like I couldn't handle it without retouching photos. My face looked flat and lacked volume, and that was what bothered me most. About two to three weeks after the surgery, most of the bruising had subsided and the swelling had noticeably subsided. Initially, my nose tip was significantly upturned, and perhaps due to the nasolabial angle correction, my philtrum looked longer than it should have been. However, after the silicone support inside my nose was removed, my philtrum length seemed to return to its natural, natural shape. These days, when I look in the mirror, I see that the natural and refined nose line I imagined in my head is slowly taking shape, so I definitely feel different when I take pictures or videos. I think I'll look even prettier once the swelling goes down a little more, so I get excited and a little thrilled every morning when I look in the mirror. Thank you, Director Kim Hyun-joo, for all your hard work.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been about 9 months since I had the surgery. I had 3 types of contouring, double eyelid surgery, and a tummy tuck all at once at ALU. I think I finally understand why they say contouring lasts up to a year. LOL. There was a time when I gained some weight, and back then, my facial line and swelling felt completely different, so I realized how important weight management was. Back then, when I was managing my weight, I woke up less swollen and my jawline felt tighter. Honestly, I had a bit of a complex about my appearance before the surgery, but now, compared to before, I think my self-esteem has gone up a lot. You know when you look at old photos? When you think about how flat and bulbous my nose was back then, you think, "Was that me?" and you want to close the window right away... That feeling of wanting to hide like a rock crab... LOL. Whenever Director Kim Hyun-joo checked my progress, she would tell me things like, "With time, your facial line will become smaller and more defined." But at the time, I just thought it was just that. But when I look back at the picture taken 5 months ago and now, my face feels like it's shrunk overall, so I'm a bit surprised that it's true... My double eyelids are now in a very natural position, and I don't really remember my flat, bulbous nose anymore. Sometimes when I look at old pictures, I think, "Wow, did they go all the way from that nose to here?" I went there thinking that ALU was famous for their autologous rib rhinoplasty, but after actually getting it done, I realized that they're also pretty good at contouring. Of course, I knew that contouring accelerates aging and sagging, and since I chose the surgery with that in mind, I think I'll have to continue taking care of it with procedures as I get older.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: After getting three contouring procedures at RYU, I thought I'd just rest my nose, but I ended up having revision rhinoplasty here again. LOL. Going back to my original nose condition... about two and a half years ago? Back then, I went to a clinic famous for their Fitmico, where they inserted septal cartilage, ear cartilage, and even Fitmico silicone. At first, I thought it was fine, but as time went by, my nose started to feel crooked... So I went back to the same clinic for aftercare and revision surgery. They suggested using my own rib cartilage. I wasn't sure at the time, so I just said, "Okay..." and followed the director's suggestion. But after about three or four months, my entire nose suddenly swelled, became thicker, and felt hot. I immediately contacted the hospital where I had the surgery, and they said it was probably inflammation, so I had to urgently have the implants removed... уЕа After the cartilage on the tip of my nose and the implants on the bridge were all gone, every time I looked in the mirror, it felt like my nose was gone... The emptiness was no joke уЕауЕа I tried to think, "Well, since they took the implants out, it's probably back to my natural nose..." But when I looked at old photos and later, it felt a little more... damaged than my original nose. From then on, I thought, "I'll have to get another nose job someday. This is unavoidable. My faith in hospitals that are famous or have a lot of advertisements just vanished." Just because they're famous doesn't mean they'll succeed... I realized it after experiencing it myself, really. So when I was looking into getting my nose done again, my biggest thought was, "I'll do my best with my own, no matter what. I can't get another infection." I was also worried that something bad might happen again. At the time, I searched everywhere for rhinoplasty and read a lot of blog posts by rhinoplasty doctors. Most of them seemed to stick to one surgical method, but Dr. Kim Hyun-joo's posts showed that she uses whole costal cartilage, sliced costal cartilage, and even minced costal cartilage wrapped in fascia. I was immediately drawn to this surgical method because it felt like there weren't just one fixed method, but rather a variety of options for each case. Plus, the surgeon also mentioned that he would take responsibility if any problems arose later, which was a huge plus. уЕауЕа Since my skin is thin, I was told it could be visible, so we decided to go with the most conservative approach. After discussing it, I had minced costal cartilage wrapped around the fascia and inserted into the bridge of my nose. It's now been two weeks since the surgery, and I've been diligently taping my nose. The tip and bridge of my nose are a little red, so I was wondering what it was, but I was told it's because the nose was raised higher than before. If you have any concerns about an inflamed nose or contracture, I recommend consulting with Director Kim Hyun-joo. She provides detailed explanations, and she meticulously assessed my case, so I'm feeling a bit more at ease.

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: First, I want to talk about my nose. уЕЛуЕЛ I really liked the side profile from the moment the cast was taken off. When viewed from the side, the nose line was pretty, so I was already satisfied, but the front view was the problem. At first, the tip of my nose looked really round and chubby. уЕа It felt a bit puffy. But now, after two months, I can really feel the difference in the swelling of the tip of my nose from the front. It feels like the bulbous nose correction was done properly, so now I don't avoid the front view when taking pictures. уЕОуЕО Maybe because I also had the osteotomy, my nose bridge looks much sharper than before. I used to have a slightly protruding mouth, but after the nasolabial angle correction, the philtrum was pushed forward nicely, so my mouth looks less protruding. So, my side profile overall feels more three-dimensional and organized. As for the contour, the line I initially wanted was exactly like Go Yoon-jung's line... That's the style. Of course, there was swelling right after the surgery, so I was like, 'Is this right...?' I wanted to, but recently, as the swelling has gone down, my facial lines have become smoother, so every time I look in the mirror, I think, "Ah, this is the process of creating something." Compared to the beginning, the swelling has gone down a lot, but the facial contours will continue to go down for up to 6 months, so I'm looking forward to my cheekbones and face shape becoming slimmer in the future. It's been about two months since I got my eyes, nose, and facial contouring done all at once, and I feel it the most when I take pictures. In the past, I spent a lot of time touching up this and that in Photoshop to get a great shot... Now, even if I just do a little skin retouching, I can take a rough picture and it turns out okay, so the time I spend editing has drastically decreased. At ALU Plastic Surgery, Director Kim Hyun-joo really takes care of everything, so I jokingly call her "Kim Hyun-joo's dad"... уЕауЕа It feels like she gave me a new face, so thank you so much...

ым╕ызеы│Аъ▓╜_en_US: It's been a little over a month since I got my jawline and nose done at ALU, and I'm only just now writing a review. уЕЛуЕЛ The swelling was so bad at the beginning that I was completely out of it... My original concern was that I had no chin + a low, wide nose, so if you look from the front, you can kind of fake it with shading, but if you look from the side, the middle of the face just looks sunken, right? You know that feeling? уЕа Especially when you look at the side, your nose is so low and sunken that I've always wanted to fix that. So from the beginning, my main goal was to improve my side view... ! I searched a lot for reviews to find a place that was good at both jawline and nose, and that's when I found ALU Plastic Surgery. I made an appointment for a consultation right away. They took a CT scan first and explained my bone structure, and they said there was absolutely nothing to shave down for my square jaw, which surprised me. уЕЛуЕЛ It didn't feel like they were randomly recommending this or that; it felt like they were just telling me the truth. My cheekbones are a bit on the large side, but the doctor clearly told me that it was optional and that I could do it or not. He also told me honestly that since I have a bit of fat on my face, if I shaved my cheekbones, more fat could accumulate on my cheekbones and deep cheeks... That's when I really started worrying seriously. I kept wrestling with whether to just get my chin done or get my cheekbones done as well... I was concerned about my chin and double chin, so the doctor strongly recommended chin advancement. He said that if he just pushed my chin forward, my thick double chin, jawline, and jawline that I was concerned about would all improve at the same time. After hearing that, my mind was almost inclined towards chin advancement. After much deliberation, I decided to just get my chin done! I also said that I wanted my face line to resemble Karina's, and for my nose, I showed her the nose shape of a beauty YouTuber who had uploaded a rhinoplasty vlog on YouTube and asked her to do it like this. When I did, she said it was definitely possible and explained in such detail the points I needed to keep in mind, the areas I needed to be careful about, and the shapes I needed to avoid. Before I knew it, I had booked surgery that very day... haha. The surgery involved a chin advancement procedure, where the chin was pushed forward 4-5mm and pinned in place. However, she said that simply pushing it forward could make the chin look longer, so she shortened it slightly and pushed it forward at the same time. Listening to her explanation, I was a little impressed by Director Kim Hyun-joo's attention to detail;; Since this hospital often uses autologous ribs for reconstructive rhinoplasty and reconstruction, she used autologous rib cartilage for the tip of my nose and thinned the bridge to make it look natural. Since my nose is already quite short, I also had a short nose correction procedure. I'd heard beforehand that the clinic was famous for reconstructive rhinoplasty, so I'm very happy with how it looks now, so I'm not worried about the surgery. I only had a chin contouring procedure, but since it involves bone grafting, my face looked completely uneven right afterward... уЕЛуЕЛ I was wondering if this was a person or just a lump of swelling, so I didn't have time to write anything and was busy looking in the mirror to get my mind together, and it started to feel a little like a human face after about a month, so I'm only leaving a review now. I've been taking pictures continuously since the first and second weeks, so I've been diligently recording the changes. These days, when I look in the mirror, I feel like my nose looks like the YouTuber I originally showed you and Karina's face shape has become somewhat similar, so I'm just looking at it with satisfaction on my own уЕОуЕО

During the procedure, the anesthesia medication was injected quite slowly, but if it was sped up too much, it would hurt immediately. So, I kept asking, "Doctor, please slow down a little bit," several times. Even a slight increase in speed would immediately trigger a feeling, so I kept asking for a speed adjustment. As for the medication... I think it activates the sympathetic nervous system a bit more, but it did make it feel like I was falling asleep a little faster. It's not that I'm completely sleep deprived, but my sleep schedule and patterns feel a bit different than before. However, my appetite has definitely decreased. Since it's a type of sleep that takes effect immediately, I've been consciously managing my water intake and minding my intake and excretion.
